		<div class="entry-content"><div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/10/20/growing-american-exports-one-small-business-at-a-time/" data-title="Growing American Exports, One Small Business at a Time" data-description="Right now, only 350,000 or so American companies export their goods and services. ">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><h6 class="kicker"><a href="//boss.blogs.nytimes.com/category/capitalizing-on-china/">Capitalizing on China</a></h6><p class="summary">An American tries to expand into China.</p></div></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><a href="//www.trade.gov/">The International Trade Administration</a> is like no other federal agency. Its theme for this year is âDare to Be Greatâ â not the kind of rallying cry you expect from government administrators.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Iâve <a href="//boss.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/05/05/helping-small-companies-go-big-in-china/">written before about the United States Commercial Service</a> and how it can help small companies looking to do business overseas. Recently, I met with <a href="//dealbook.nytimes.com/2013/11/07/white-house-names-senior-bank-of-america-executive-to-commerce-post/">Stefan M. Selig</a>, Americaâs under secretary for international trade. Mr. Selig heads the International Trade Administration, which oversees the group.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âWe are the only part of the government that is charged specifically with helping businesses,â he said. âThere is no topic more important to a C.E.O. then how they grow their business â and if you talk about where growth is going to come from in the next decade for U.S. companies, it is going to be in tackling some of these overseas opportunities.â <span id="more-89424"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Only about 305,000 American companies export their goods and services. Iâm passionate about encouraging businesses to get a footprint in foreign markets: Growing our economy requires looking beyond our borders.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">One way to get started is with the Commercial Serviceâs <a href="//export.gov/discoverglobalmarkets/">Discover Global Markets</a> series of informational seminars. I recently spoke at one in New York, and was impressed by the insight and expertise of the consultants, entrepreneurs, and government officials running the sessions. People with deep knowledge of local conditions shared their advice on entering and sustaining an overseas business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The Commercial Service has outposts in 75 countries and offers surprisingly specialized services. Entrepreneurs looking to grow in a particular region can arrange individual meetings with foreign service officers who work in their target country. Companies new to exporting can get start-up help, while those with experience can get one-on-one advice about specific issues, like introducing a new product line or protecting their intellectual property.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Small countries that donât get big press coverage can be especially fertile ground for small- and medium-sized companies willing to go into markets that large multinationals ignore, Mr. Selig said. In China, some of the best opportunities can be found in <a href="//blogs.wsj.com/chinarealtime/2014/04/16/what-makes-a-tier-2-city-in-china-count-the-starbucks/">the smaller cities outside the tier-one list</a> of major metropolises like Beijing and Shanghai. TheÂ  International Trade Administration maintains more than 100,000 market reports designed to help entrepreneurs make decisions about where to take their business.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Surprised that you havenât heard more about the Commercial Service and all the minimally priced, and often free, aid it offers? Mr. Selig tells a revealing story. During his confirmation process, when he met with a group of senators, one who sits on the Senate Finance Committee told him: âStefan, you seem like a very talented guy, and Iâm sure you will get confirmed, but I just donât know what you are going to do over at the I.T.A.â If a senator on the finance committee â presumably one of the more business-savvy committees in Congress â doesnât know about the trade association and what it actually does, thereâs no doubt that itâs a well-hidden secret from businesses.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">If youâre looking at getting started or growing your overseas operations, the agencyâs informational sessions are a great place to start. I hope to meet you at one.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Deb Weidenhamer is chief executive of <a href="//www.auctionandappraise.com/home.html">Auction Systems Auctioneers and Appraisers</a>.</em></p>
<div id="addendums" class="addendums"><div class="story-addendum theme-correction"><strong>Correction: October 23, 2014</strong> <br>An earlier version of this post misstated the number of American companies that export goods and services as well as the number of countries in which the International Trade Administration has outposts. The number of companies exporting goods and services is 305,000, not 350,000. And the I.T.A. has employees assisting American exporters in 75 countries, not 77.</div></div>	</div>
